vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Deteriorating</conjf>
<pr>(d⟦esl⟧*t⟦emac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*⟦osl⟧*r⟦amac⟧`t⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[L. <ets>deterioratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>deteriorare</ets> to
deteriorate, fr. <ets>deterior</ets> worse, prob. a comparative fr.
<ets>de</ets> down, away.]</ety> <def>To make worse; to make inferior in
quality or value; to impair; <as>as, to <ex>deteriorate</ex> the
mind</as>.</def> <rj><au>Whately.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The art of war . . . was greatly <qex>deteriorated</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

